\begin_layout Chapter
Methodology
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "cha:Methodology"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our proposed tracking system has the capability to handle a dense wireless
 network.
 Sensor are initially positioned on the region of surveillance, with a specific
 location.
 The location is explicitly chosen to make sure the network is optimized
 for high accuracy.
 To make sure of that, sensor should be position away from each other to
 create a larger area of surveillance.
 Once the network is configured, it will have the ability to track multiple
 targets.
 When a target approaches a sensor node, that node would calculate its distance
 between itself and the target.
 The distance acquired will become the data passed through the network and
 received by a server to map the target to particular location.
 The process would be repeated again when it approaches another sensor node
 different from the one mentioned before to update the system of the target’s
 current location.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Design
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The algorithm that we will use is the LEACH algorithm.
 It is a type of a Cluster-based Approach Targeting System.
 It has the capability to track multiple targets in regions of surveillance.
 Like every other Cluster-based algorithms it uses cluster heads that are
 the major senders of data to the server.
 They use this approach to try and minimize congestion in a network.
 When all nodes in a wireless mesh network are able to send data to the
 server, nodes would be congested and congestion leads to packet loss.
 Large quantities of packet loss cannot be tolerated by a network, especially
 for tracking systems, since the calculated positions need to be accurate.
 Even if the network would implement mechanisms to minimize packet loss,
 the system would still encounter problems in terms of the delay of arrival
 of packets.
 Immediate reception of the packets is needed to provide a location of a
 target that is close to or even in real time.
 An architecture of a Clustered Wireless Sensor Network is shown on Figure
 .
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Implementation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In creating a wireless mesh network as a target tracking system, we will
 first make sure that the nodes can both transmit and receive data.
 Using the received signal strength and a digital compass, the location
 of each close node must be determined by one specific node.
 An algorithm would be developed in order to flood the network in such a
 way that collisions would be minimized and classify which nodes belong
 in each cluster.
 Nodes that are isolated would automatically be chosen to be their own cluster
 head while in clusters that contain 2 or more a head node would be determined.
 Head nodes for each cluster would be determined depending on the charge
 of their respective battery, the one with the most charge would be head
 node.The head nodes would be the only ones to send the data of the whole
 cluster so that congestion would be minimized when the base nodes are accepting
 data.
 After the base nodes receive the data they would triangulate the position
 of each head node in order to determine the exact location of each node
 in the mesh network.
\end_layout

